# Novell
**Category:** ventures  
**Domain:** enterprise software / networking  
**Website:** [https://www.novell.com](https://www.novell.com) (historical; now part of OpenText)

## Overview
Novell was a software company founded in 1979 in Provo, Utah. It became a dominant force in enterprise networking through its flagship product, NetWare, a network operating system that provided file and print services, directory services (Novell Directory Services, later eDirectory), and network management for local area networks (LANs). At its peak in the mid-1990s, NetWare held an estimated 70% of the PC LAN market.

The company also acquired several notable products, including WordPerfect (word processing), Unix System V source code (enabling its own UnixWare), and the Digital Research files. After facing stiff competition from Microsoft’s Windows NT and declining market share, Novell struggled to transition. It was acquired by Attachmate in 2011, then by Micro Focus in 2014, and now operates under OpenText following Micro Focus’s acquisition in 2023.

## Utah connection
Novell was born and grew in Utah’s “Silicon Slopes.” Its Provo headquarters anchored a wave of tech entrepreneurship in the state, and many of its alumni went on to found or lead other Utah tech companies. The company’s legacy helped establish the region as a hub for enterprise software and networking.

## Key people
- **Ray Noorda** – CEO from 1983 to 1994; often called the “father of network computing”; turned Novell into a market leader.
- **Dennis Fairclough** – co-founder and initial developer of NetWare.
- **Jack Davis** – co-founder and early business leader.
- **Eric Schmidt** – CEO from 1997 to 2001; later CEO of Google.